hands_on_practices.solution:
Start from the given partial widths:
$$
\Gamma(\phi\to\nu_L\nu_R)
=\frac{g_S^2\,M_\phi}{16\pi}
\Bigl(1-\frac{4m_\nu^2}{M_\phi^2}\Bigr)^{1/2},
$$
$$
\Gamma(\phi\to\nu_L\nu_L+\nu_R\nu_R)
=\frac{g_P^2\,M_\phi}{16\pi}
\Bigl(1-\frac{4m_\nu^2}{M_\phi^2}\Bigr)^{3/2}.
$$
By CP symmetry, each same-helicity channel is equal, so
$$
\Gamma(\phi\to\nu_R\nu_R)
=\tfrac12\,\Gamma(\phi\to\nu_L\nu_L+\nu_R\nu_R)
=\frac{g_P^2\,M_\phi}{32\pi}
\Bigl(1-\frac{4m_\nu^2}{M_\phi^2}\Bigr)^{3/2}.
$$
The ratio is
$$
R
=\frac{\Gamma(\phi\to\nu_R\nu_R)}{\Gamma(\phi\to\nu_L\nu_R)}
=\frac{\frac{g_P^2\,M_\phi}{32\pi}
\bigl(1-\frac{4m_\nu^2}{M_\phi^2}\bigr)^{3/2}}
{\frac{g_S^2\,M_\phi}{16\pi}
\bigl(1-\frac{4m_\nu^2}{M_\phi^2}\bigr)^{1/2}}
=\frac{g_P^2}{2\,g_S^2}
\Bigl(1-\frac{4m_\nu^2}{M_\phi^2}\Bigr).
$$
